[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Smith is a 48-year-old woman referred for treatment of rectal cancer.  She was noted to be anemic in November, and started passing blood per rectum in December.  She also noted more abdominal "gurgling" and narrowed bowel movements with alternating constipation and diarrhea.  Her first colonoscopy March 3, 2010, was positive for a-1-cm sigmoid colon polyp (tubular adenoma low-grade dysplasia) and a rectal mass at 10-cm (invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma).  Pathology results are confirmed by Ottumwa Regional Memorial Medical Center.  No staging studies have been performed to-date, and her bleeding has resolved.
Comorbidities include hypertension an diabetes mellitus for which she uses medication.  Her only previous surgery was pilonidal cyst treatment at age 18 and cholecystectomy with tubal ligation in 1991.  There is no history of heart attack, stroke, bleeding disorder, anesthesia reaction, medication allergy, sleep apnea, or thrombosis.  She does not smoke.

